pational name for a steward or official, from Old French <i>baillif</i>. Compare   Bailey   4.","French: habitational name from (Le) Bailly, the name of several places in the northern part of France."]},{"name":"Bale","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived by the outer wall of a castle, Middle English <i>bailli</i>, <i>baile</i>, from Old French <i>bail(le)</i> ‘enclosure’ (see   Bailey   3).","Breton (<b>Balé</b>): variant of   Balay  .","French: unexplained."]},{"name":"Baily","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayly","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Bayley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]},{"name":"Balay","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Rajesh, Satish.","Altered form of English   Bailey  .","French: habitational name from any of various minor places so named."]},{"name":"Baile","meanings":["Spanish: status name for a steward or official, from Old Spanish <i>baile</i>, Late Latin <i>baiulivus</i>; cognate with English   Bailey  .","French (southern): variant of   Bail  .","English: variant of   Bale  ."]},{"name":"Baillie","meanings":["Scottish:","from Older Scots <i>baillie</i>, <i>baili</i>. In Scotland, a baillie was a status name for any of various officials, including the chief magistrate in a barony and (later) the chief magistrate or administrative officer of a barony or district. Etymologically, this is the same word as English   Bailey  , but the functions as well as the spelling of the two officials were different in England and Scotland.","topographic name from Older Scots <i>bailli</i> ‘outer court of a castle’; see   Bailey   3 and   Bale   1."]},{"name":"Baley","meanings":["English: variant of   Bailey  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":1,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":46,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Margaret Bailey was born in 1336, in Rugeley, Staffordshire, England. She married Walter Bailey in Shropshire, England. They were the parents 